{"actual_usd":0.160675,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":324,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31163,"reply":"\"Yeah, I think the naturalistic options get thinner the closer you lean on the actual shape of the thing.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the bright square, where a bicycle wheel clicks as somebody coasts over the bridge stones.* \"Grief visions might explain one or two people saying they saw him. They do a much worse job with the empty tomb, the stubborn publicness of the claim, and the fact that a scared, disappointed group turned into people willing to suffer for saying not just 'we felt him with us' but 'God raised this man from the dead.' That is a weirder sentence than private consolation.\"\n\n\"And the 'maybe he didn't die' line always feels especially weak to me.\" *I rub my thumb along the edge of the bench once, thinking it through.* \"The Romans knew how crucifixion worked. A half-dead Jesus limping out of a tomb does not produce resurrection faith. It produces pity, panic, and a need for bandages. It does not produce 'he has conquered death.'\"\n\n\"Which doesn't mean insisting on supernatural because we like dramatic endings.\" *I give a small shrug.* \"It means the claim the witnesses are making is already supernatural in kind. If the best natural explanation keeps leaving major pieces on the floor, eventually the honest move is to admit they're claiming a miracle. Not as a mood. As the most fitting explanation of why Christianity exists in the shape it does.\"\n\n\"What part feels most live to you — the visions idea, the survival idea, or the basic allergy to miracle claims in general?\"","rolling_24h_usd":90.36972999999999,"run_id":"9b168371-6115-4a06-9afd-ab091fff4bd6"}
